[]: Cruel Angel Thesis Clip &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by Legend of the Past &raquo; Sat Jul 08, 2006 6:19 am Hello everyone, I&#39;m Legend of the Past. I hope to be active and enjoy things here, and be helpful in discussions to come. So, onto discussion. I&#39;ve been watching an high quality version of Cruel Angel Thesis on YouTube, and saw all the things flashing there-Embryonic and Mature Adam, young Gendo Ikari, Rei sitting naked with her knees covering her torso next to what looks like a glass of water, SEELE logo, a part of the earth burning, etc etc etc... One intresting flash appears right at the last five seconds, where you see several shots of Shinji face, and then you see him shielding himself from some kind of light. It&#39;s really hard to focus on them in regular speed, because the moment you try to focus on one shot, you miss another two. That felt reminiscent of hidden messanging and use of flashes, a sort of hypnosis. My guess is that the subconsious does realize and catch those images, so that if you see the video in good quality, you can see things like Embryonic Adam and feel like you&#39;ve seen it before. It&#39;s a try to make you feel like a part of the show. I&#39;m sure you know a similar thing happans with &#39;Komm, Susser Todd&#39;. The song&#39;s clapping makes you want to clap along, and the repeating of the chorus at the end makes you sing along. The chorus is short and very catchy, built of two five word sentences &#40;&#39;It all comes tumbeling down&#39; and &#39;I just keep letting me down&#39;&#41;, but the repeat chorus cuts it down to shorter sentences &#40;&#39;Letting me down&#39; and &#39;Tumbeling down&#39;&#41;. That makes the song all the more catchy and seductive, makes you want to sing and clap along. KST was composed by Anno himself, and is the song that plays during Third Impact. By singing along and clapping along, you &#39;give up your individualty&#39; and become instead of a listener another singer, you join the group. Also, the singing and clapping makes you feel like you can&#39;t always tell your voice from the singers, and like Rei says, the Sea of LCL is an ambigious world, where you can&#39;t tell where you begin and others end. Anno&#39;s a fricking genius, even if the methods he makes you become part of the show can really frighten you the moment you realize.

